STATE OF CONNECTICUT STATE OF CONNECTICUT DEPARTMENT OF PUBLIC SAFETY DEPARTMENT OF PUBLIC SAFETY DIVISION OF PROTECTIVE SERVICES DIVISION OF PROTECTIVE SERVICES Terrorist Threat Condition SEVERE: A terrorist attack has occurred or credible and corroborated intelligence indicates that one is imminent.
Normally, this threat condition is declared for a specific location or critical facility.
Threat Condition Critical Facilities Protective Action Continue all precautions from lower Threat Level.
Â¨ Announce Threat Condition SEVERE and explain expected actions.
Â¨ Deploy security personnel based on threat assessment.
Â¨ Close or restrict entry to the facility to emergency personnel only and restrict parking areas close to critical buildings.
Â¨ Maintain a skeleton crew of essential employees.
Â¨ Deploy emergency response and security teams.
Â¨ Activate state EOC.
Â¨ Maintain close contact with state and local law enforcement.
Â¨ Be prepared to implement mutual aid agreements with government and with other critical facilities.
Â¨ Provide security in parking lots and company areas.
Â¨ Report suspicious activity immediately to state and local law enforcement.
Â¨ Restrict or suspend all deliveries and mail to the facility.
Emergency or essential shipments should be sent to an off-site location for inspection.
Local Government Actions Continue all precautions from lower Threat Level.
Â¨ Announce threat condition SEVERE to employees and to the public explaining anticipated actions that should be taken.
Â¨ Deny unauthorized access to critical facilities and infrastructure.
Continue 100% inspections of personnel, vehicles and packages to the extent allowed by law.
Â¨ Visually inspect the interior and undercarriage of vehicles entering parking lots and terraces.
Â¨ Deploy equipment assets and ensure physical security measures be afforded to critical sites.
Â¨ Assemble trained volunteers to include Citizen Corps, USAR and the American Red Cross.
Â¨ Implement Mutual Aid Agreements as required.
Â¨ Continue to assess the vulnerability of key assets and facilities.
Take appropriate action to protect them by deploying appropriate security forces to these sites.
Â¨ Cancel or delay unnecessary employee travel and leave.
Â¨ Activate the Emergency Operations Center.
Â¨ Control release of information to the public and news media.
Â¨ Send a Public Information Officer to the EOC.
Â¨ Provide security for personnel dispatched to repair or restore damaged facilities and system.
Public Response Guidelines Continue all precautions from lower Threat Level.
Â¨ Closely monitor news reports and Emergency Alert System radio/TV stations.
Â¨ Be suspicious of persons taking photographs of critical facilities, asking detailed questions about physical security or dressed inappropriately for weather conditions (suicide bomber).
Report these incidents immediately to state and local law enforcement.
Â¨ Report suspicious activity and call 911 for immediate response.
Â¨ Avoid repeating unsubstantiated information and rumors.
Â¨ Expect delays, searches of purses and bags and restricted access to public buildings.
Â¨ Expect traffic delays and restrictions.
Â¨ Take personal security precautions to avoid becoming a victim of crime or terrorist attack.
Â¨ Avoid crowded public areas and gatherings.
Â¨ Do not travel into areas affected by the attack or to an expected terrorist target.
Â¨ Keep emergency supplies accessible and automobile tanks full.
Â¨ Be prepared to evacuate your home or shelter-in-place on order of local authorities.
Â¨ Assist neighbors who may need help.
